/* Manual
  
Structures:
Child article is linked to parent article by PARENT_ID column, which is the ID of an article item. A parent article serves only for displaying the name in the menu and do not need content. Also, menu name comes from TITLE_ALIAS column or a parent article, which is a shortened plain text version of the title. For child articles under a parent article, display orders are from POSITION column. Articles with null value in PARENT_ID column are top level articles. So to construct the full menu structure, get top level articles by selecting articles with null PARENT_ID. Then check if there are articles with PARENT_ID pointing to the ID of each article. If so, make the article a parent article. If not, this article will be the end of the branch.

Title and contents:
TITLE and CONTENT columns will be displayed on the main page for a non-parent article. Both contents are plain HTML. Basic HTML elements are supported including <h>, <p>, <br>, <span>, <b> and styles in these tags. Other advanced elements like <div>, <iframe>, <a>, etc are not supported. <img> tag is supported but not in the normal way. It will be covered below.

Cells and content displaying:
The SG main page is a table view. Title is in its own cell and contents may be in one and multiple cells. Contents will be split into multiple cells if there are image cell, image text cell, text image cell or table cell. A new cell will be created for image related cell(tag) and if there are text content after the new image, these texts are places in another new cell. For table tag, each table cell will be in its own cell in the table view.

Special self-defined tags:

<img> tag: 
Sample format <img src="x.jpg" height="y" width="z"/> x is the name of the image in main bundle. y and z are the actual pixel number for height and width. When displaying an image, the image itself will take a cell. The image view will be created with 20 pixels less than the width of the screen(10 pixels padding on both side). The height of the image view will be calculated base on the proportion of value x and y.

<imgtxt> tag:
Sample format <imgtxt src="x.jpg" height="y" width="z">i</imgtxt> x, y and z are the same as img text explained above. For i which is the content between the open and close of the image text tag, it is the text part. The image will be place on the left side the text will be on the right side. Text supports HTML fonts and height is calculated base on the text view width. Then the cell height for this image tag cell will be the higher on of image and text. Image and text will when be centered vertically in the cell.

<txtimg> tag:
Sample format <imgtxt src="x.jpg" height="y" width="z">i</imgtxt> The same idea with image text cell. A text image cell is just simply reversing the left right order of text and image.

<tab> tag:
Sample format <tab>x<tbr>y<tbr>........</tab> x and y will be place in two cells of a table. each cell is separated by <tbr> tag and there can be as many <tbr> tag as you want between the open and close of <tab> tag. Table cells will be surrounded by solid lines.

<div> tag:
Sample format <div color="x">y</div> Div block puts content inside, which is the y, into a cell with full color described by x. The color will also be the overall theme of the article. y is the content in html. Note that only the first div block sets the overall theme color. The rest of the div will show the color cell but won't change the top bar colors.

*/

